defaultWritten evidence submitted by the defaultFdefaultood and defaultDdefaultrink defaultFdefaultederation (FDF)default&#xa0;
defaultThis written evidence is submitted by the Food and Drink Federation, the trade association for food and drink manufacturing. Food and drink is the largest manufacturing sector in the UK (accounting for 15% of the total manufacturing sector) turning over £78.7bn per annum; creating GVA of £20bn and employing up to 400,000 people.
default&#xa0;
defaultExecutive Summarydefault&#xa0;
defaultFood security is fundamental, not only to individual well-being but to all wider human social and economic activity. It is also an extremely complex issue dependent on many different factors and variables. UK food security cannot be seen in isolation from what is happening elsewhere in the world. But, as the Committee recognised in its 2009 inquiry, there is potential for us to do more at a national level to address the challenges which have since been comprehensively articulated in the Final Report of the Government Office for Science Foresight Global Food and Farming Futures Project
default published in January 2011.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn essence these challenges involve producing more, from less and with less impact against a background of world population growth, increased pressure on natural resources and the need to mitigate and adapt to climate change.
default&#xa0;
defaultOther contributory drivers such as increasing urbanisation, demand for higher protein diets in developing countries and the apparently more frequent incidence of extreme weather events, notably droughts and floods, are widely recognised as reinforcing the need for greater resilience and sustainability across the whole food system, in terms of both production and consumption.
default&#xa0;
defaultFood and drink manufacturing plays an essential role in driving resource efficiency and supplying consumers with a wide range of safe, nutritious, appetising and affordable products, as well as contributing to economic growth and supporting rural and other communities by offering many different employment opportunities.
default&#xa0;
defaultBut improvements are needed at all stages of production, from the raw materials we source, to the energy, water and other resources we use in processing, through to helping consumers in the choices they make.
default&#xa0;
defaultScience and technology have the potential to make a major contribution to the innovation required to make food which is healthier, more sustainable and more affordable for everyone.
